I want to work with the Division of Family and Children Services to help abused or neglected children and support troubled families. I have these important values for the social work field: service, respect, ethics, helping others, and improving myself. These values are very important to me.

I have always wanted to help people, but I did not know what career to choose. In high school and college, I saw people running from their problems. I decided to study psychology. After graduation from Piedmont College in 2009, I took a break. One day, I met a sixteen-year-old boy who was escaping his abusive parents. I spoke to the police and his parents. This made me think about a social work career.

Social justice is also important for social work. Society says each person is unique, but we often try to be like everyone else. I am unique and do not like being limited. In high school and college, I protested against social injustice: by changing my hairstyle, wearing unique clothes, piercing my ears, and joining GSBA. I also fought against racism and discrimination. I will always stand for social justice.

The paper talks about Biological and Sociocultural models and how they relate to insomnia. The Biological model looks at genes and medical health. The Sociocultural model looks at environment and how it relates to race, ethnicity, and money. The paper explains research about these models and their findings. It also says what is good and not good about each study.

Insomnia is a sleep problem. It can be:
- Primary insomnia: hard to sleep or stay asleep.
- Hypersomnia: hard to stay awake.
- Narcolepsy: fall asleep suddenly.
- Breathing problems while sleeping.
- Sleep-wake cycle problems.

Other sleep problems can cause insomnia. They can be:
- Due to mental health problems (Axis I or II).
- Due to medicines or medical problems.

The Biological model says that sleep is controlled by neurons in the brain called orexin. These neurons have a receptor called GABAB. When this receptor is active, it helps sleep. If it is not active, it can cause sleep problems. A study with mice showed that a drug that makes the receptor work better can help sleep. This means that people with problems with this receptor might need medicine to sleep well.

The Sociocultural model says that if this receptor is inherited, it could affect sleep. This could make it hard to do school, work, and daily tasks. The paper says this is a serious problem.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) is when the brain does not process what we hear well. It is not the same as being hard of hearing. People with CAPD can hear normally, but they may have trouble hearing in noisy places or understanding what is said. They may also have other problems like not knowing where sounds come from or having trouble with speech patterns.

CAPD was first called "auditory imperception." In the 1950s, researchers started to study it. In 1961, a man named Kimura created a test for it. A meeting in 1977 helped more people study CAPD.

CAPD can cause many problems. People with it might not hear sounds well in space. They may also have trouble with speech patterns or sounds that change. They might not understand the order of sounds or use clues from sounds to act.

To diagnose CAPD, people use tests and observe how the person listens. No single test works best. Many tests use sound and ask people to notice certain items. Some tests use sounds from the ear to measure responses.

CAPD is not caused by anything known. It is not clear why people get it. There is no cure, but help can make it better.

Teachers can help students with CAPD in a mainstream classroom. They can make sure the student sits near the teacher, repeat what they say, and use simple words. They should also keep the classroom quiet when possible.

Twelfth Night shows that pretend dressing is useful for tricks, but can cause problems. When a trick ends, the person may feel alone. They must decide: save self or keep friends. Some will be upset. Gender trick is hard. Why dress as opposite? Viola pretends to be man to protect self. She feels lonely and confused. Olivia loves Cesario, but loves Viola too. Shakespeare shows deception helps find feelings. Olivia changes love from Cesario to Sebastian. She loves Cesario/Viola like sister.

German rule in Africa was known for being harsh. Many people say it was brutal, especially with how the Ovaherero and Nama were treated. The colonial empire was big and covered many places. It had different rules and ways of life in each place. Education was also different. In East Africa (now called Tanganyika), the British found many educated Africans. German teaching in other colonies was also good. But in South West Africa (now called Namibia), teaching was mostly done by religious groups. The government did not help much. More money went to teaching Europeans. This made a big difference. Even after German rule ended, many people in South West Africa were not educated. Many things like weather and settlers helped make this happen. This paper wants to talk more about these things and look at new studies about settlers and how they thought about Africans. There are many books about teaching in the German empire. Most are in German and from the early 1900s. They talked about how schools worked. Later books in English compared teaching in different colonies and talked about it in more detail. Cohen wrote a book about teaching in South West Africa and East Africa. He said the big settler population in South West Africa made its teaching system different. South West Africa was not as hot as other colonies. There were more whites there than in East Africa.

Popular music has many types. There are so many that it's hard to list them all. Most types have many smaller types. The type called Heavy Metal is one of the most big and different types of music. It started about 40 years ago. It has grown to be many different things.

Heavy Metal is different because it has many ways to show feelings. The feelings it shows are often dark. It also has many people who play their instruments very well. Metal also has many drugs. People use drugs to help them make music. The music they make is different from other music. It has a lot of bass, volume, and very loud sounds.

Heavy Metal started with a song called "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles. This song is different from other Beatles songs. It shows a dark feeling. This song helped start Heavy Metal. It was a response to a song by The Rolling Stones.

Metal has grown to be many different things. It has many types of music inside it. But all these things have one thing in common: they are dark and loud. This is what Heavy Metal is.

Henri Rousseau was a painter who dreamed of being accepted by other artists and art lovers. He began painting when he was old. He worked at a job for many years before he started. He wanted to be like other famous artists. He painted a dream in 1910. He had a difficult time making this dream a reality. He wanted to be unique but also wanted to be accepted. This shows his struggle.

Henri Rousseau was born in Laval, France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer. He had no formal art training. He worked for France as a customs inspector. He lost his wife and many children. He started painting to feel better. He hoped to be like other artists.

Rousseau wanted to be accepted in the art world. He painted at the same time as famous artists. He didn't get recognition until later. He and Matisse were different. Matisse wanted to be unique. Rousseau wanted to be accepted.

Henri Rousseau's dream painting shows his struggle to be unique but also accepted.

Many people think ethics and beauty are connected. I think this is true. John Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty." We learn about beauty and ethics from life or study. But, we also feel them without learning. They are like trying to explain why something is good or beautiful, not just rules. Talking about art or morals can't fully explain why they are good or beautiful. People often say, "There's just something about it," when asked about their favorite art or literature. Ethics and art have a special power. They can't be fully explained. This is like "je ne sais quoi." This power makes them connected. We feel them deeply, but cannot fully explain. Literature is especially connected to moral values. McKean said, "Literature is important to us because of the values we find there." This is why ethics and art are connected.

Germany is strong and united. It has many different cultures, from Munich in the mountains to the sea city of Kiel. This culture also can be felt in Cologne on the Rhine, through the middle of Germany, to the city of Dresden by the Elbe. Germany is made from many different sources and tribes.

Germania is the old land of the Germans. The name comes from a Germanic tribe called Tungrians. They lived in the land before the Romans. Some people say the name comes from a spear used in war.

Tacitus, a Roman writer, wrote about the Germans in 98 AD. He said the Germans were from old tribes and not mixed with other races. He said they came on boats, not land, because Germany was not easy to live in.

The Romans did not live in Germania. They went there to get goods and fight. They took some Germans into their army. This happened in the early days of the Romans.

I looked at a picture. I did not feel anything. My mind worked. It looked at the picture. I thought about what I saw. The picture was a bowl of fruit on a table. I wanted to draw it. I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." It teaches how to draw.
I tried to use a technique from the book. I tried to put a square frame around the bowl. I could not do it. I was too amazed. I felt like an artist.
I wanted to draw the bowl. I held a pencil. I moved my hand. I drew the bowl. I tried to move the toilet. It was stuck. I tried again. It was still stuck.
I cleaned the toilet. I used a mop. I stood up straight. I looked at the toilet. I was happy. I finished my work.

Teenagers die when they drive. This happens because they are not ready. Their brains and experience make them more likely to have accidents. They also have more accidents when they drive with friends. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center showed this in a study.
California and other states try to keep teens safe by limiting their driving time and passengers. But this is only a small help. Teens are not ready to handle driving risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman says even 18-year-olds are too young. He thinks 19 or 20 would be better.
The Baby-Boomers' children will soon drive. This will add many new teen drivers. More accidents will happen.
Schools can teach driving to future drivers. But no one under 18 should drive alone. A permit can be given first, with some practice driving. The number of hours can be like those in most states.
Nationwide laws can help protect teens. It is a good idea, but it is not new.

I looked at many old Edison films in the Library of Congress. I chose to study all the trick films, which were 15 from 1895 to 1901. These films use tricks to create illusions. My study mainly described the style of trick films and their special parts. Most early trick films were set in one place. They did not move the camera. They used long and medium shots, not close-ups. This is like theater and vaudeville. Actors move side-to-side, not towards or away from the camera. For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors move back and forth but the camera does not follow. Long shots and medium shots are common. Close-ups are not used. These films are usually short, about a minute or less. They often show simple tricks, like magic or disappearances. In trick films, one idea can be shown in many small shots. For example, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), the film of Mary's "head" is not one shot, but many shots joined together to make the illusion of her head being cut off.

John Taylor from Caroline liked Republican ideas. He worked in farming and politics. He spoke strongly about freedom and government. He wanted to protect and support farming. His views on government came from this.

Taylor thought the United States could make a perfect system. There was no old tradition to stop it. He believed in human rights and that they depend on each other. Government must not take these rights away. He thought strong people often did bad things. But in society, this should not happen.

For a good society, Taylor wanted a government that understands good and evil in people. He said, "Government is done by people, so all its good and bad must be human." He thought a good government must protect property, help farming, and stop capitalism. He believed that people act for self-interest, but this should be for the public good. A good government must keep people's evil nature, but it must be watched closely.

Taylor wanted a strict Constitution. He wanted a small federal government with only the powers stated in the Constitution. He knew a big government might be bad. But he thought a simple, literal interpretation could be wrong. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true guide of the United States.

In Figure 17, there was a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month. This was not good. It is hard to know why this happened. In the third month, it was cold and people did not commute to campus by bicycle or on foot. Many students and teachers were busy with school work and holidays. The project had a lot of energy at the start, but this decreased. To fix this, we created a special Carpool Challenge Week. This week had more log submissions. Another problem was that people like to drive cars. To change this, we gave out gift cards for local stores and restaurants. We could have given out more prizes, like a bike or a hybrid car, to get more people involved. If the prizes got bigger over time, it might have helped. The gift cards were good at the start, but more prizes might have helped.

An ETF is a security that follows an index or a group of assets, like an index fund. It can be traded like a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer many benefits, such as diversification and the ability to sell short. They have lower fees than mutual funds. However, ETFs also have a downside: you must pay a commission for each trade. There are many types of ETFs available. It is important to check if the benefits are real. In this study, we will compare the ETF IHF with its top 10 holdings. We will look at their returns and risk. We will also check if a portfolio of these 10 stocks is better than buying the ETF. The top 10 holdings make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. We will use these holdings to calculate the portfolio's return and risk. From the results, we can see that a portfolio of the top 10 stocks could give a higher return with less risk. However, we need to check if this difference is statistically significant. To do this, we will calculate the standard deviation of each stock and compare it to the ETF.

Poe’s poem "Dream-Land" has special words. Thulé is one of these words. Poe used Thulé in lines 6 and 56. A scholar named Mabbott said this word comes from Virgil. Virgil wrote about a cold island north of Britain. But there is another source for Thulé. Poe read German writers. One was Goethe. His poem "Faust" has a short poem called "The King of Thule". In this poem, a king loses his wife and his will to live. Poe’s "Dream-Land" has similar words and feelings.

Goethe wrote "Faust" in two parts. The first part was published in 1808. The second part was published in 1832. Poe wrote "Dream-Land" around the same time. He may have read "Faust" and used it for his poem.
Poe used Thulé twice in his writings. He used "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum". He also used Thulé twice in "Dream-Land" as the start and end of the poem. "Dream-Land" and "The King of Thule" can be read together. In "Dream-Land", the speaker talks about a dark, lonely Thule. The speaker sees a world without color, and is haunted by dead friends. This is like the king in "The King of Thule". Both the king and the speaker in "Dream-Land" feel lost and lonely.

Poe knew Goethe because he liked another writer, Tennyson. Poe also would have read Goethe’s work. Many people copied Goethe’s work after his death.

California law might allow customer Jennifer Palmer to get money for being harmed in a slippery applesauce spill at a store. She can show the store manager was bad because he knew about the spill twice and did not clean it quickly. He was eating dinner when he could have cleaned the spill. Six people had already slipped and fallen in the store before Palmer's accident. Her lawyer can argue that the manager should have known the spill would cause harm. However, the argument might not be very strong because the manager did not mean to cause harm. The manager also did not think the spill was a big problem. Palmer might still get some money for her injury, but it could be hard for her to get extra money that is called punitive damages. This is because punitive damages are not easy to get in California. California law says they are for bad people who hurt others on purpose or without care. Courts say conduct is bad when a person knows they might cause harm and does nothing to stop it. Palmer's lawyer will need to show the manager did this to get punitive damages.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. We talked about if Islam is a bad religion. I think this question is important today. After 9/11, media views on Islam changed. In 2001, a president named Barack Obama with a Muslim background couldn't have happened. The Prophet Muhammad's life story in books is interesting. It says Muhammad was a good man who didn't force people to become Muslims. People liked his teachings and joined him. There are stories like Jesus' miracle of multiplying food for many people. These stories make Muhammad seem like a good prophet who didn't need to prove himself. This is like copying Jesus' life. Many stories are told by people who heard from other people. This makes the stories seem less true. The book also says Muhammad was a good man, but history says otherwise. I think Muslims know the truth about Muhammad's life.

The teachings of Jesus were forgotten as Christian thoughts changed after his life. History shows that Christianity moved away from its start. Today, people are more aware and want to change. Some people want to keep old beliefs. In the future, Christians will learn more about history. They will want to know what Jesus really taught. It will take many years, but the trend will change. People will stop following other ideas. They will only follow Jesus' teachings. The church will be strong and lead the way. People in different places will have similar beliefs. History has many reversals. Christians were once hated by the Romans, but the Romans became Christian. Our country went from slavery to leadership. In the future, Christianity will change back to its start. People will understand Jesus' words as symbols, not as facts. What happened after Jesus' life? Before Christians, there was Judaism. It had one God and holy books. People had different beliefs. They were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and common people.

I think The Jungle shows how people are naturally greedy and selfish. They care only about themselves and their own lives. The book shows this clearly in many ways. One example is the owners and managers of big factories. They want their companies and factories to be very big and successful. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets hurt by their factories. According to Upton Sinclair, "'The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world'." Sinclair wants to show the great damage caused by this pollution. The owners do not care about the smoke coming from the factories or the waste from the animal pens. They do not care about their workers either. They want to make more money, so they make workers work long hours and lay off many people without notice or compensation. In that time, there were few laws to protect workers. This allowed managers and owners to make workers work in bad conditions. The book does not say it directly, but the workers who worked themselves to death in Packingtown were expected to live with the bad conditions. There were no agencies or organizations to help workers. Unions were formed, but they often did more harm than good by making money from the poor workers. Workers were so badly treated and had no way to escape the system that they were like slaves. "'Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery.'"

Many authors use different ways to make readers feel or think about important subjects. Some ways are better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these ways in his novel The Great Gatsby. He does this by using words together in unusual ways. He also gives special meaning to some colors like gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In his novel, Fitzgerald gives special meaning to these colors and then uses them to give readers a feeling about important things.
Fitzgerald uses white/gray to show that something is important or not. He does this by using both colors together in the beginning of the novel. People are mostly wearing white. For example, Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby’s party, and Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle. Also, many things are white or gray. For example, the dog-seller is a gray old man, and the Italian child on the railroad is gray.
After Fitzgerald gives white/gray special meaning, he uses them to show that something is not important. He starts with Daisy. When she is described as dressed in white, readers start to see her as not important. Fitzgerald does this with other things around Daisy too. For example, there is a gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar, and she is again in a white dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is good for farming. It is sunny and warm. Farmers grow many things like tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, and peaches. People in San Diego want organic food. They wait long for organic eggs and milk. Organic farms have tours. They also have space for hiking and birdwatching. This is good for the landowner and wildlife.

Organic farming has more work. It needs more people. It is more expensive. It has fewer crops. But it helps many animals and plants. It is better for the environment.

The land is near the town of Potrero. It has 160 acres of different plants. It is next to the Cleveland National Forest. It is in a special plan for many plants and animals. Some are in danger.

People lived here a long time. They were Native Americans. Later, people used it for cows and wood. This land was part of a small farm. It was used for a long time.

The owner looked at government programs. They want to save money and help wildlife. They found a model organic farm in the area.

Culture is important in negotiations. Culture means what it is and what it is not. Culture is different everywhere. It is not the same in every place. It is not always easy to understand. Cultural statements that say “all people from one country are the same” are not always true. It is important for a negotiator to understand how culture affects the talks. When a negotiator visits another culture, he compares it to his own. This can help him understand the other culture better. A negotiator should accept the other culture for what it is. He should work within its rules, especially if he is in a weak position. If a negotiator is on foreign ground, he should respect traditions and beliefs. This can help to overcome cultural barriers and make the negotiation better.

Culture is not only about countries. Companies within a country also have their own cultures. For example, some companies expect long work hours. Others have a more relaxed schedule. A company's culture can be seen in how employees dress, how they communicate, and how they hire people. Some companies encourage all kinds of philanthropy. Others only allow company-approved charities. Looking at American companies is a good way to see how different they can be. Some cultures are not as complex as American culture. They may seem uniform, but they are not.

Values are also important in a culture. They explain why a culture is like it is. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not publicly shame his company. If a culture values strong bargains, a negotiator will not settle too quickly. Understanding these generalities before negotiations is important. However, learning about the other negotiator on a personal level can make the negotiation better.

The Bible says, "The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This phrase is in Psalm 14 and starts St. Anselm’s argument about God. Thomas Aquinas also believes in God. Both men want to prove God's existence. We must compare their arguments.

St. Anselm’s argument says that God exists in our minds. We cannot think about God not existing. This is faith. It means we believe in God without needing proof.

Thomas Aquinas says we can prove God's existence with reason and facts. He gives five reasons: change, cause, order, degrees of excellence, and harmony. For example, if you have all but one puzzle piece, you know it must exist.

Long ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince became Buddha. He left the world and became wise. His teachings created Buddhism. Today, the most common form of Buddhism is called Theravada.

Buddhism changed over time. In Sri Lanka, people have a water-cutting ceremony. The ceremony is not taught by Buddha. It is a change in Theravada Buddhism. This change happened because of many reasons. Some were from inside the Buddhist community. Others were from outside.

Buddhists believe in the Triple Gem: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is the three baskets of Buddhist texts. They have rules for living. For lay people, there are five rules. Monks have more rules. The most important teaching is the Four Noble Truths. The first truth is that life has suffering. The second is that desire causes suffering. The third is that suffering can be ended.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The worst part was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. The United States won and took Texas and the Southwest. Many other fights happened too. This rivalry started because of differences in religion, culture, and interests. Nations that share a border often argue over these things.

Many other nations also have long rivalries with their neighbors. David M. Pletcher says that Mexico and Cuba have long problems with the United States. He explains that these nations are close to the United States, but they have been rivals. Other Latin American nations usually have good relations with the United States.

Religious issues made the US-Mexico rivalry worse. Sally Frahm says that Americans have often been against Catholicism and monarchy. This is like the Cold War, but it was about religion instead of politics. The US-Mexico rivalry began because of the distrust between the English and Spanish. This made it hard to have good relations.

Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between Mexico and the US. Most of these were about borders and raids. Bandits and outlaws caused problems until both countries used military force. The rivalry stopped when Mexico became dependent on the US, and when American goals changed from taking more land to helping Mexico's economy.

Fifteen years ago, I got sick suddenly. I was a nurse but now I cannot work. I have no money. I live on Social Security. I have no things of my own. I am not strong. I could not have lived without my family and friends. People need to help each other. I agree we need to help each other, not just look to the government. We should trust each other again. We should ask for help. We are stronger together. People in the US should know each other and help each other. I have a disaster kit. I am prepared. I have food, water, and lights. I also have a small farm. We should trust others and help each other in big and small emergencies.

Why do animals change over time? Is there anything that affects how they change? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that scientists cannot describe even simple animal shapes with math. But now, math is used to study how some animals grow and change. Our study uses math and experiments to find out how animals like Prunum change. We look at X-ray pictures of Prunum to find numbers that can show how the shell changes. We use these numbers in a math program to guess how the shell might change. This helps us understand bigger changes in this group of animals over time.

A shell is like a tube that turns around in space. The turns are called whorls, which go around like a spiral. The center of the shell is called the columella. The biggest turn is at the end of the shell, and the other turns are called the spire. The pointy end is called the apex, and the flat end is called the base. The animal comes out of the shell through an opening called the aperture.

You can look at a shell from different sides. The most common way is to look at the aperture. A method to count the turns is to look from the apex, find the first line between turns, and count the turns from there.

A shell grows like a trail of openings through time and space. You can trace the path of these openings using math. Once you have a math formula, you can change numbers to see how the shell might change.

The number of deaths among babies and newborns in Indonesia has not changed much for ten years. The country is close to meeting many Millennium Development Goals. However, health improvements for children and mothers are not good enough to meet the goals by 2015. We will discuss reasons for this below. We need to improve the health system.

Indonesia has more births with a skilled health worker. But many of these workers are not doctors. They cannot help with complicated pregnancies. So, there are many maternal deaths. Also, fewer children under five with diarrhea are getting treatment. There is no good data on postnatal care, but it is a problem.

Cesarean rates are low, about 4%. Rates are higher in cities, 7%, than in rural areas, 2%. This shows that urban areas have better access to healthcare. There is also a big difference in healthcare access between poor and rich people. The poor have more problems getting healthcare services.

To improve health for babies and mothers, we need to decide how to fix the lack of services. Should we use special programs or improve the whole health system? Special programs are easier to manage and can help quickly. But they can also hurt other parts of the health system and create duplication.

Victorian novels focus on details and the rich people of that time. Two novels that are different are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. They use mystery and strange things to make characters stronger. They show what makes people feel and act. For example, in Oliver Twist, there is a dream about shooting. It shows Oliver's fear and lack of control over his life. This dream also shows the bad things happening to him and how he can't change them. He feels powerless and sad. He can't even try to save himself because he is too scared. This dream reinforces the idea that Oliver has no control over his life. Even when his life is in danger, he doesn't try to change anything. This shows his defeat and sadness, perhaps because of Fagin's influence. This dream makes the story more interesting and helps us understand Oliver's feelings.

In Wuthering Heights, there are also dreams and strange things. They show the characters' thoughts and emotions. The dreams help us understand the characters better and make the story more interesting.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program. I helped young students with their schoolwork. I was good at English and reading. One student, Adrian, was having trouble reading. His problems were strange. He knew some letters, but others, not at all. He spoke perfect English, but his mother only spoke Spanish. When I met his mother, I understood. Adrian could read, but he didn’t know the English alphabet. I hope he does better now.

I tell this story to talk about the language barrier in schools. Even children who speak English can have trouble reading. This problem is common. What can we do? For Adrian, tutoring helped. But for children who speak little English, it’s more difficult. There is no easy answer. We need to combine many things. Here are some ideas.

First, the dual language system is good. It helps children whose first language is Spanish. It also helps all children. Children in these programs do better in school. People sometimes think it’s a waste of time. But that’s not true. If we use this system more often, all children will benefit. How? We don’t need all teachers to be bilingual. But special teachers who speak both languages can help.

From the time we are small, we are told about something bigger than us. Some go to Sunday school. Others go to temple or search inside. Many accept what parents teach. But some reject it. We find our own way to spirituality. We search for light in darkness.

My father's favorite bird is a cardinal. We sat on our porch. He looked out. His hair was thin. He was sick. I felt alone. I hugged him. He died in December. I did not go to watch. I remembered him by how he lived. I did not want to watch him die. I did not want to see his family watch. I was alone for three days.

No one called me.

Gothic novels are a mix of old and new. They are called 'Gothic' because they include old ideas and new ways of writing. Ian Watt calls them a "Gothic Novel." People say they are good or bad. Some think they have no real depth. Others like them for the 'terrible sublime' feeling they give.

The first Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, uses old theater ideas and new novel styles. It shows old and new things together. Walpole uses "old" theater and "new" nature to create "Gothic stories." The Gothic genre has old theater, architecture, and traditions. The word "Gothic" means old or simple. It was used to describe many things in the past. It was seen as old compared to new society and literature.

The Gothic genre uses chivalry, a knight's training, from the middle ages. Chivalry is important because it shows brave, honorable knights. Gothic writers use it to show the idealized and romanticized past. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a time of political trouble. He was worried about the future. He may have thought the good morality of the past was lost. The character Frederic in the novel shows this. He is described as a gallant and courteous knight. His story shows chivalry and tragedy.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from order to customer. It includes planning, doing, and controlling. Keith Oliver, a consultant, began this idea in 1982. There are six main parts: production, supply, inventory, location, transport, and information. Business managers use these parts to serve customers well.

- Production is the first step. This is the start of the whole process. It decides when, why, where, and how to make things. Managers need to know what customers want. They use the market to find out. After knowing customer needs, managers decide what to make and how much. Then, they choose where to make it and which plant is best. They also plan workloads and equipment maintenance. Production is very important. Each detail matters. If not planned well, it can cost much time and money.

- Supply is the next key part. Supply means deciding the core abilities of a place and choosing partners to outsource work. A company may have many divisions for one product. Each has different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager picks the best division for each process. They may also choose to outsource work to other companies to be quick, have flexibility, and keep costs low.

A sign says, "Hitler lives in Burma."

Ellen Page, actress from Juno, stands alone on a street with a cardboard sign. The sign says, "Hitler lives in Burma." Burma, also called Myanmar, is in Southeast Asia. A bad group is in charge there. They took power in 1962. In 2007, people protested. Many were monks. They wore orange clothes. The government let them gather, but then it became violent. Many people were hurt or died. A man named Kenji Nagai was killed. The government did not let journalists see what happened.

This is not new. Many governments are like this. They want no one to disagree with them. The Roman emperors thought they were chosen by gods. The Japanese emperors were believed to be gods. Our president talks with a leader from a group called "Stupid People." Many people died in recent events. In China, many people died in 1989. In Rwanda, many people were killed in the 1990s. Hitler's "Third Reich" also killed many people.

Duke Ellington's music is famous for his ability to write music for his band. His piano skills add subtlety to his compositions. As a composer, he wrote many complex pieces that showed each band member's skills. He also wrote music that allowed soloists to improvise freely. Ellington's music often emphasizes the sound of the band as a whole. His use of instruments like voice and trombone adds texture and color. For example, in "Creole Love Call," the voice is used like a musical instrument. This piece has a call and response between the voice and other instruments. Another example is "Hot and Bothered," where the muted trumpet and scat singing create a rich sound together. Ellington's music often uses the style of his soloists to complement the music.

She always wanted something. It started when she was 14 and continued to 17. She thought she wanted a boy, but no one interested her. She wondered why. She lived life, always thinking about this. A day at home was usually calm. Her parents were good, calm people. They argued rarely. Today, she heard a cry from the kitchen. She ran to her mother. Her mother was on the ground, in pain. "Take me to the hospital," she said. Her daughter helped her to the car and drove to the hospital. The hospital smelled of disinfectant and sickness. Her mother fell from a stool trying to get a vase. She was taken to be seen by doctors.

This study showed that eating a Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a high alternate Mediterranean diet score, can reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. The alternate Mediterranean diet includes more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes. It also has more healthy fats and fish, and less animal products and saturated fats. Some alcohol is allowed.

Other studies have found that following this diet can help prevent heart disease and improve cholesterol. This study did not look at stroke or stroke death.

The study followed 74,886 women from the Nurses' Health Study. This study has 121,700 female nurses in 11 states. The study asked nurses about their food every year for 20 years. They used this information to calculate a diet score. More than 95% of the nurses stayed in the study for 20 years. The study also looked at other factors like smoking, exercise, and weight.

The study used a method to reduce random changes in diet. It looked at the diet score over two years. It also adjusted for things that could affect the results, like age, smoking, and exercise.

The study found that following the Mediterranean diet can reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. There were 2391 heart disease cases, 1763 stroke cases, and 1077 deaths from heart disease or stroke over 20 years. Women who followed the diet the most had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke compared to those who followed it the least.

In 2007, America had a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs, the housing market became very bad, and important companies lost money. This problem is still happening today. We need to know how it happened and how to stop it.

The problem started because banks and other companies made bad decisions. They gave loans to people who could not pay them back. Then they put these loans into special packages and sold them. When people could not pay, the banks did not have enough money. This made the problem worse.

This happened in the 1990s during President Clinton's time. He wanted to be popular. So, he made it easy for people to get loans. A reporter wrote about this in 1999. He said that some companies were in trouble because they had too many loans.

Many things made the problem worse. Some of these were special kinds of loans and packages. People and businesses had too much money in the housing market. This made them very weak.

The housing market suddenly got worse. Many banks and companies lost a lot of money. Some of them were sold or had to change. Fannie and Freddie, which had a lot of loans, were taken over by the government.

Exposition is the part of a story where you tell readers what happened. Dr. Merlin thinks it is not always good. She says, "Show, don't tell." She also says exposition can be boring.

In a story, exposition is when a character tells another character a lot of information. In a book, the author does this. An example is when you read about a heroine and her husband. You are told they met, got married, and he was killed. This should not take a long time. You should see how they feel about each other. This explains why their love is special.

As a writer, you should show what happened. It is hard to write this part. You may want to skip it. But it is important to show the reader what happened, not just tell them.

I watched two news programs from Columbus, Ohio. The first was NBC 4 this morning on August 13, 2011. The main story was about a man named Shad Hostettler. He stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. The police arrested him. They showed his picture. He looked very bad.
The second story was about a man named Travis Buyers. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He is very sick. The police are looking for the person who shot him. This story was shorter. I think this is because Travis Buyers is black. I have seen this happen before. The news does not talk much about black people who are hurt or killed.
The next story was about a hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. The police think a rifle shot it. They are offering a reward for information.
The next story was about rain and thunderstorms on Saturday. The weather will be warm.
The next story was about a robbery at a store called Clime Road UDF. A black man robbed it. He was wearing a hoodie. He is about six feet tall and weighs about 150 pounds.
Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He is a convicted drug dealer. He was sentenced to 300 months in jail. He is Hispanic.

A bond between brothers is strong and cannot be broken. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other better than anyone else. They see themselves in each other. When a bad or good situation happens, this bond shows its true nature. These feelings have a high cost. Understanding these feelings is important. When a brother looks at another brother's eyes, they see their true self. Their actions and the results show their true character. In the book "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers face these feelings. They go on a tough journey. They have strong, opposite feelings. In the end, one brother dies. The story shows these feelings through the main character, Doodle, and his brother's actions. The narrator also shows Doodle's feelings. These feelings greatly influence Doodle's actions.
The main character's feelings are mostly pride. From the start of their adventures, he feels angry towards Doodle. He wants Doodle to be like him. Doodle cannot do many things because of his weak heart. The main character wants to teach Doodle like he would a normal brother. But Doodle cannot do these things. This makes the main character feel bad. He even thinks about killing Doodle. But when Doodle smiles at him, his heart melts. The story shows that the main character's feelings are complex. He has love for Doodle deep inside him.

The human brain is like a big computer. It has many parts that work together to process information. The brain changes as technology changes. In the past, it was compared to different things, like a wax tablet, a book, and now a computer. These comparisons help us understand the brain better, but they can also be wrong.

Information starts when we see, hear, or feel things. The brain changes these signals into something the brain can use. This happens in two ways: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up means the brain looks at small parts and puts them together. Top-down means the brain uses what it thinks to help it understand.

There are many steps in processing information. Each step decides what is important. The brain picks out things like names more than other things, even if they are in a noisy place. There are many types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Working memory stores information for a short time. Long-term memory stores information for a long time.

Many ways show how the brain stores information. Some are based on how people remember things. Others are based on computer science or how the brain works in animals. One way is the semantic network. It says that ideas are like nodes. They are connected to each other based on how related they are.

Aldous Huxley discusses problems with technology and capitalism in Brave New World. People in the story like community more than individual. They are taught to want happiness right away. Citizens are like pieces in a big game. The World Controller decides what they do. The story shows the author's thoughts about the problems with these systems.

Huxley uses Marxist ideas to tell this story. He uses words like "homogeny" and "reification." These show the problems with the economy. Capitalism is shown as a bad thing because people are not free to know about other classes. They want to make money and buy things. This is called "false consciousness." People do not know about the real world because they are taught to like money and buying things.

People in the story are not free. They cannot make their own choices. They are told what to do. They do not think about other people. They only care about money and buying things. This is called "hegemony." People do not know that they are being controlled. They think they are free. They only care about their own class. They do not care about other classes.

People in the story do not have real feelings. They do not love or hate. They only talk about money and buying things. They do not think about other people. This shows the bad effects of capitalism. People always obey their class. They do not think about being free.

I have been at University Park for about two and a half years, which is four and a half semesters. Many students, like me, find getting around campus difficult. My first year, I lived in East Halls, far from the center. Walking to classes could take 25 minutes, especially in bad weather. Now, this empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As our campus grows, getting around becomes harder.

My friend said, "Bikes are great. They are the best way to travel on campus." I agree. They are efficient and good for your health. I live off campus, near the center. My smartest decision this year was to buy a bike. It takes five minutes to bike to my class in Thomas building, compared to 25 minutes by walking. Bike paths are not always easy, but it's better than walking. Without a bike, walking would take an extra 30-40 minutes each day. That's over two and a half hours every week.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that is designed to track an index, a commodity or a basket of assets like an index fund, but is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange.  An ETF gives you the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership like the ability to sell short, buy on margin and purchase as few as a one share in any transaction.  Though these benefits are extremely attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are far lower than those of the average mutual fund.  Unfortunately, there are some down sides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would pay on a stock order.  Another benefit of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available.  Though these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good exercise for the savvy financial investor to evaluate whether stated benefits, like diversification, do indeed exist, and the extent to which they exist.  For the purposes of this effort, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it against the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the benefits of a owning a single ETF come close to the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and also whether or not there are better configurations of the same stocks that would provide a more optimal sharp ratio or return.
	In order to evaluate the ETF, it would become rather unwieldy to include every holding, therefore we have decided to include only the top ten holdings accounting for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF.  Below are the top 10 holdings and the percentage of total assets.

	In order to gain an estimation of how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to  calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolioâ€™s Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion that the ETF has established through their holdings.  The calculations of Beta and return are included in the below chart.

From the above chart it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns.  It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is .12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  From the results completed thus far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta.  However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.
	In order to evaluate whether or not these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% in order to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a precipitous drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. That was a bit disheartening, and it is hard to say why that might have happened. With the onset of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a drop in people commuting either by bicycle or by foot, which may account for some portion of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is very busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so forth. Filling out the commuter log might just have slipped off the radar screen for many folks. In addition, December brings the onset of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which time many do not even need to come to campus at all. Classes then resume for the spring semester in late January, perhaps also a clue to the low number of logs for that month. But none of that really explains the low number of submissions for February. One might also conjecture that any project of this type is going to have an initial burst of energy and excitement at the outset, which might then naturally decline. In an effort to combat this trend, we created the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to try and reinvigorate the initiative, which did result in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we experienced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of both a natural decrease in engagement, but also specifically the problem of holiday and semester breaks experienced in higher education. 
Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative modes of commuting. We gave out a lot prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores.
